## Decision

- **Smallest practical standalone browser model:** Ternlight Mini. It is the
  lightest audited registry-contained model, embeds queries quickly, and was
  successfully validated in the target DevPod and Chrome `file://` flow.
- **Higher-quality registry-contained backend model:** the bundled MiniLM Q8
  artifact from `@plurnk/plurnk-mimetypes-embeddings`. The model, tokenizer, and
  ONNX Runtime Web assets are present in the NPM tarball. The package itself
  declares Node `>=26`; the DevPod builder therefore extracts its static assets
  and uses Python ONNX Runtime instead of executing its Node API on Node 22.
- **Ternlight Base:** a reasonable browser/server middle option when the extra
  few megabytes and latency are acceptable. It was not part of the completed
  GoTo browser benchmark, so its relevance and startup trade-off must be measured
  before replacing Mini.
- **Multilingual requirement:** none of the audited multilingual rows ships its
  weights inside an approved NPM/PyPI artifact. They remain unusable under the
  current registry-only policy unless the organization mirrors a pinned model
  artifact into NPM or PyPI.

The current GoTo descriptions are English, so Ternlight Mini and MiniLM are
appropriate for document embeddings. An Italian query is not guaranteed to map
correctly into that English vector space. If cross-language Italian-to-English
search becomes a hard requirement, use a real multilingual model and rebuild
all document vectors; do not mix multilingual query vectors with existing
English-model document vectors.

## Important interpretation notes

### “Runs locally” is not the same as “ships offline”

Transformers.js, Sentence Transformers, FastEmbed, Chroma, and RuVector all run
inference locally after model acquisition. Their normal constructors still
resolve model files from a model hub or configured URL. This is why their rows
are marked ❌ even though their marketing correctly describes local inference.

### Model size versus runtime size

MiniLM's 21.91 MiB Q8 ONNX file is not the entire standalone-browser cost. The
validated browser runtime also embeds tokenizer files and about 12.86 MiB of
ONNX Runtime WASM. Conversely, Ternlight fuses model, tokenizer, and inference
engine into one WASM file, so its model-only weight size cannot be measured
separately.

### Model identity is part of stored data

Vectors from different models, revisions, quantizations, pooling rules, or
normalization rules are not comparable. Persist the complete model identity and
re-embed the corpus after any change.

